helperText.isIn:
The student's answer needs to lie within a specified interval or set. Enter the number of unique items the student needs to return. Put the required interval or set in the EXPECTED ANSWER field.#{
ewline[1em]	ext{Expected:\enspace}[0.3,0.6]
ewline[0.5em]#} and with "#{1#}" in the box.#{
ewline[0.5em]	ext{Correct:\enspace}0.4,\quad	ext{Incorrect:\enspace}0.2
ewline[0.5em]#} If the student needs to return #{2#} numbers, then a possible valid answer would be #{0.35,\enspace 0.45#}

helperText.satisfies:
The Student's answer needs to meet the given in/equality or equation. Enter the number of items that the students needs to return. Put the condition in the EXPECTED ANSWER field. Note that you can only use one variable, e.g. x.#{
ewline[0.5em]	ext{Expected:\enspace}x>2
ewline[0.5em] 	ext{Correct:\enspace}3,\quad	ext{Incorrect:\enspace}1
ewline[0.5em]#} If the student needs to return 2 numbers, then a possible valid answer would be #{3,4#}

helperText.allowedUnits:
Students can only use these units. Equivalence between common units is considered.#{
ewline[1em]	ext{Expected:\enspace}1kg,\quad	ext{allowed units}=g,kg
ewline[0.35em]	ext{Correct:\enspace}1000g
ewline[1em]	ext{Expected:\enspace}2500m,\quad	ext{allowed units}=m,km
ewline[0.35em]	ext{Correct:\enspace}2.5km
ewline[0.35em]	ext{Correct:\enspace}2500m#}

helperText.graphTolerance:
Tolerance for simpler objects like polygons is checked by considering the distance to the closest points that make up the object for the student's entry vs the expected answer.#{
ewline#}For lines and conic sections, the objects are converted to a standard form equation and then the parameters of the form are checked that they each meet the tolerance.#{
ewline#}These are the forms that are used:#{
ewline[1em]	ext{Line:\enspace}ax+by=c
ewline	ext{Circle:\enspace}(x-h)^2+(y-k)^2=r^2
ewline	ext{Ellipse:\enspace}(x-h)^2/a^2+(y-k)^2/b^2=1
ewline	ext{Hyperbola:\enspace}(x-h)^2/a^2-(y-k)^2/b^2=1
ewline	ext{Parabola:\enspace}4p(y-k)=(x-h)^2
ewline[1em]	ext{For example:}
ewline[1em]	ext{Correct Answer:\enspace}x^2+y^2=4#} and tolerance of #{0.1.
ewline#}The student enters a circle which is equivalent to the equation: #{x^2+y^2=4.5
ewline#}This will be graded as wrong since the expected #{r=2#} for which #{2.1#} would be an ok value and #{2.1*2.1=4.4#}

helperText.graphPointsOnAnEquation:
There are two scenarios:#{
ewline[0.5em]#}1) You give an object such as a line or circle and require the student to enter any   two points that lie on the object.#{
ewline#}2) You provide an equation, #{	ext{e.g.\enspace}y=x+1\enspace#}and the student needs to enter points that lie on this equation.#{
ewline[0.5em]#}You can also use inequalities in both scenarios.

